    <h2>Disclaimer Indicators</h2>
    <h3>Using Numerals</h3>
    <p>Use numerals to show disclaimers in footnotes and endnotes. The first item that's disclaimed within the creative should be indicated with a 1, and each subsequent item should be marked with the next consecutive numeral in order of appearance.</p>
    <p>If multiple pieces of creative, such as display ads, are driving to the same webpage, then the indicator(s) on the creative should be determined by what's on the webpage. For example, if a disclaimer on a landing page is marked with a 3, then the display ad that's driving to that landing page should use a 3 as well – even if there are no other claims on that display ad.</p>
    <p>Keep in mind that disclosures, such as our <a href="https://brandcentral-dss.rhicms.com/quicken-loans/search-results/component-search-results.htm?xid=x171">National Licensing Disclosure</a> and <a href="https://brandcentral-dss.rhicms.com/quicken-loans/search-results/component-search-results.htm?xid=x1011">Copyright Statement</a>, don't need any indicators since they're not tied to a specific item within the creative.</p>
    <p>Our old system of indicating disclaimers, which included asterisks, daggers and other symbols, is outdated and shouldn't be used. As of July 18, 2018, all new creative should use numerals to indicate disclaimers.&nbsp;<strong>The only acceptable exception</strong> is the use of the dagger (†) as an indicator of a disclaimer in promotional copy on Rocket Mortgage.com that typically appears in a banner. Examples include flash sales, Cyber Monday, special pricing promos, etc.</p>
    <h3>Placement</h3>
    <p>Avoid putting indicators in logos, headlines and other prominent places; instead, try to keep disclaimer indicators within the body copy of the creative.</p>
    <p>In copy, place the indicator outside of punctuation.</p>
    <p>In footnotes or endnotes, begin each disclaimer with its corresponding indicator. Don't include a space between the footnote indicator and the disclaimer.</p>
    <h3>Typography</h3>
    <p>The indicator should be superscript both within the body copy and within the footnote or endnote.</p>
    <p>The indicator should use the same font and weight as the body copy. If the indicator must be placed within a headline or a logo, use a font from nearby body copy if possible. The indicator must be legible, but it should also be as unobtrusive as possible. &nbsp;</p>
    <p>*For Direct Mail, all font must be 10-point or larger.*</p>
