<section id="section-3">
    <h2>Multi-State Examination</h2>
    <h3>Compliance Takeaways</h3>
    <h3>1.General Advertising</h3>
    <ol style="list-style-type: upper-alpha;">
        <li>All claims must be substantiated (regardless of in advertisements, banker scripts, or banker training videos) must be substantiated prior to going live.</li>
        <li>Any superscript, daggar, or other type of reference marks must be no smaller than two font sixes smaller than the substantive text.</li>
        <li>Always assume debt-to-income (DTI) at 43% for all calculations.</li>
        <li>Advertisements where products advertised are impacted by a consumer’s DTI the maximum price adjustment for DTI must be applied to the advertised loan terms.</li>
        <li>ARMs must not be advertised as our lowest rate; ARMs must be described as a “low introductory rate.”</li>
        <li>When advertising an interest rate, APR must always immediately follow AND be displayed with equal or greater prominence.</li>
        <li>
            When an advertised interest rate is discounted, the advertisement must clearly and conspicuously disclose the cost of the discount points as a dollar amount.
            <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
                <li><em><strong>Applies To:</strong></em> Any advertisements where interest rates are discounted.</li>
            </ol>
        </li>
        <li>
            Disclosures of points must also note that they are “paid at closing”
            <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
                <li><em><strong>Example:</strong> </em>You could finance a $200,000 loan at a fixed interest rate of __% (__% APR) for the cost of 1 point ($2,000) paid at closing.</li>
                <li><em><strong>Applies To:</strong></em> Any advertisements that include points.</li>
            </ol>
        </li>
        <li>
            Disclosures of trigger terms may appear on the back of advertisements, but must appear in the same font, size, and shade as the advertising content or terms triggering the disclosure. If the disclosure is on a social media asset or website, the disclosures must be in close proximity to and prominently displayed; if leveraging the “one-click-away” exception the links must be equally displayed and labeled as “Legal Disclosures.”
            <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
                <li>Link must be the same font and size, however may be distinguished as a hyperlink with an alternate shade</li>
                <li>Link must drop into the page exactly where the disclosure terms start. The consumer should not have to scroll to find the terms.</li>
                <li><strong><em>Applies To:</em></strong> Any advertisements containing trigger terms, especially direct mail.</li>
            </ol>
        </li>
        <li>
            Advertisements with a ‘New Monthly Payment’ that is calculated without prepaids (taxes, insurance, or escrow) must include a disclosure directly above, below or next to the new monthly payment OR a conspicuous hyperlink one-click-away within such proximity, that links directly to the required disclosure.
            <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
                <li><em><strong>Applies To:</strong></em> Any advertisement where ‘New Monthly Payment’ is provided.</li>
            </ol>
        </li>
    </ol>
</section>
<section id="section-4">
    <h3>2.Direct Mail Advertising</h3>
    <ol style="list-style-type: upper-alpha;">
        <li>Direct mail extending a firm offer of credit must state the consumer has been “Pre-Selected” for the advertised offer.&nbsp;</li>
        <li>Direct mail extending a firm offer of credit must leverage data that assumes gross monthly income is based on the minimum income that that would be eligible for the advertised loan amount.</li>
    </ol>
    <h3>3.Flash Sales</h3>
    <ol style="list-style-type: upper-alpha;">
        <li>
            Flash sales must only be redeemable by clients responding to the advertising
            <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
                <li>Pricing for consumers responding to the advertisement compared to those who don’tmust be shown and reflected in order to substantiate.</li>
                <li><em><strong>Applies To:</strong> </em>All flash sales; company-wide pricing and discounts/sales must also undergo testing and monitoring of consumers receiving such pricing.</li>
            </ol>
        </li>
    </ol>
    <h3>4.Core Digital Media / LowerMyBills</h3>
    <ol style="list-style-type: upper-alpha;">
        <li>The LowerMyBills (LMB) landing pages must have the relevant disclosures on the page when a consumer is directed to the page and must appear above the footer fold.</li>
        <li>All LMB disclaimers and disclosures must be approved by the Rocket Mortgage Marketing Compliance team prior to go-live.</li>
    </ol>
</section>
<section id="section-5">
    <h3>5.Mortgage Banking / Banker Scripts</h3>
    <ol style="list-style-type: upper-alpha;">
        <li>Banker scripts must prompt a banker to quote APR whenever quoting an interest rate (see 1F above).</li>
        <li>
            Banker scripts must NOT include any claims below:
            <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
                <li>Suggesting a client can “skip a payment” or “increase cash reserves through an escrow refund” by refinancing.</li>
                <li>Suggesting Rocket Mortgage gets wholesale pricing on its retail loans. Or reference to lower costs from RMs amount of volume.</li>
                <li>Suggesting VAL gives buyer the strength of a cash buyer or that it is the next best thing.</li>
                <li>Suggesting a VAL is a “full approval.”</li>
                <li>Using any absolutes like “best” “cheapest” “lowest.”</li>
            </ol>
        </li>
    </ol>
